{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/soft-vs-hard-equality/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Abel L. Mbula"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"3de19060-bd76-5fcd-b7ac-a2d029dfc845","excerpt":"We often need to compare values when we are programming. To check for equality in JavaScript, there are more than one way of doing it. You can use either a…","html":"<p>We often need to compare values when we are programming. To check for equality in JavaScript, there are more than one way of doing it. You can use either a double equals operator, ==, aka “soft equality” or the triple equals operator, ===, aka “hard equality”.</p>\n<p>Let’s see them in more detail.</p>\n<h2>The Soft Equality</h2>\n<p>It only checks for equality in value, not in type.</p>\n<p>For example if we assign the number 3 to a variable like this: <code class=\"language-text\">const a = 3;</code></p>\n<p>and compare it like so:\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 107px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/a36daa89a202d73377229a76b666d268/de870/a%3D%3D3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 33.64485981308411%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"a==3\"\n        title=\"a==3\"\n        src=\"/static/a36daa89a202d73377229a76b666d268/de870/a%3D%3D3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a36daa89a202d73377229a76b666d268/de870/a%3D%3D3.png 107w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 107px) 100vw, 107px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>This works fine, but there are some slight problems with double equals operator. Let’s test again with the string “3”:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 90px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/fcee60383eca7d6f544f24884e18a970/d2e30/a%3D%3D%223%22.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 40%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"a==3\"\n        title=\"a==&quot;3&quot;\"\n        src=\"/static/fcee60383eca7d6f544f24884e18a970/d2e30/a%3D%3D%223%22.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/fcee60383eca7d6f544f24884e18a970/d2e30/a%3D%3D%223%22.png 90w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 90px) 100vw, 90px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>As you can see here, the returned output is <code class=\"language-text\">true</code> when in reality it should be <code class=\"language-text\">false</code> because <code class=\"language-text\">a</code> is not a <code class=\"language-text\">string</code> but a <code class=\"language-text\">number</code>. So what happened so that we get  <code class=\"language-text\">true</code>? When soft equality is used, JavaScript will attempt\nto coerce the two values to the same type when doing the comparison. This “bad behavior” of JavaScript can lead to some very strange results. Let’s see some more examples:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token string\">\" \"</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n\n<span class=\"token string\">\" \"</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"0\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span>\n\n<span class=\"token boolean\">false</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"0\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n\n<span class=\"token string\">\"1\"</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n\n<span class=\"token string\">\"2\"</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span>\n\n<span class=\"token string\">\"true\"</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">null</span> <span class=\"token operator\">==</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">undefined</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>The snippet above shows that values that are not actually equal have a tendency to be reported\nas being equal to each other.</p>\n<h2>The Hard Equality</h2>\n<p>Unlike the soft equality, this equality operator checks for both the <strong>value</strong> and the <strong>type</strong>. It is also called a stricter equality test and returns <strong>true</strong> only if the two elements are the same. </p>\n<p>Let’s use the same example as above with hard equality and see how it will behave.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\">a <span class=\"token operator\">===</span> <span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">true</span>\n\na <span class=\"token operator\">===</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"3\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">null</span> <span class=\"token operator\">===</span> <span class=\"token keyword\">undefined</span>\n<span class=\"token operator\">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class=\"token boolean\">false</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>As you can see, <code class=\"language-text\">a</code> is equal to number 3, but not equal to the string 3. The hard equality operator also correctly reports that <code class=\"language-text\">null</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">undefined</code> are two different values. </p>\n<p>I have written a tutorial about <code class=\"language-text\">null</code> vs <code class=\"language-text\">undefined</code> that you can check here</p>\n<h2>Which one to use?</h2>\n<p>This is a good question, and the simple and quick answer is <strong>it depends</strong> upon your need. If your program does not need to check for the value type before doing operations (i.e you’re certain that both sides will still have the same type), you can go for soft equality. In the other case and by default, I would suggest to always go for hard equality. Some bugs in program are due to the use of soft equality and it is often difficult to discover them.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Understanding JS: Soft (==) vs Hard Equality (===)","date":"January 02, 2020","description":"What are == and === in JavaScript?"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/soft-vs-hard-equality/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/css-hiden-vs-none/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Understanding CSS: visibility hidden vs display none"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/null-vs-undefined-js/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Understanding JavaScript: Null vs Undefined"}}}}}